    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Gaps and irregularities behind the drywall—the \"cavity\"—can definitely matter, though usually not for the *surface finish* itself, provided you are using standard framing. However, if you have large gaps or unevenness in the framing behind the drywall, it can lead to structural issues or, more commonly, sound transmission problems. If the framing is loose, the drywall panel itself can vibrate or resonate, which sounds like a hollow, tinny noise.\n\nFor the visible finish, if the framing is sound, the drywall itself will cover it, but if the framing is crooked or bowed, that slight unevenness *will* eventually show up as a slight ripple or waviness in your mudding, no matter how well you tape. A good rule of thumb is to ensure your studs are plumb and your drywall sheets are screwed into them securely and evenly spaced.\n\nIt's a good thing you're thinking about the whole picture, not just the surface! A solid structure underneath is what keeps the whole assembly from feeling like a poorly constructed, wobbly tower of mud and gypsum.\n\nIf you're worried about a specific area, you might want to gently tap the drywall with a piece of wood—if it sounds hollow in",
